{"timestamp": "2025-12-06 16:40:23.019821", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting Diagnosis Report\n\nScope and goal\n- Validate end-to-end service reachability for hosts in 10.<core>.<dist>.0/24 toward server farm 10.200.0.0/24.\n- Verify OSPF health across core, distribution, and server-access layers.\n- Confirm DNS/DHCP paths and web service access (web0.local…web3.local, and web99.local via Nginx).\n- Ensure backend web servers are not reachable directly from user subnets.\n- Identify any anomalies, localize faulty devices, and assess likely root causes (no remediation proposed).\n\nSummary of findings\n- Overall network health is good. OSPF adjacencies are Full where expected; routing tables are consistent; hosts can reach required services.\n- DNS resolution for web99.local and web0.local succeeds and maps to correct addresses.\n- HTTP access to the load balancer (web99.local) is successful with stable timings.\n- Backend isolation is working by design: backend servers in 20.200.0.0/24 are reachable from the load balancer but not from user subnets.\n- Minor performance observation: web0.local shows higher TTFB and total time than through the load balancer, suggesting application or server-side latency on web_server_0 rather than a network fault.\n\nEvidence and details\n\nReachability (ICMP)\n- General reachability across many hosts and subnets shows 0% loss and low latency (typical RTT 1–5 ms), indicating healthy L3 connectivity.\n- From host_1_1_1_1 and host_2_1_1_1:\n  - dns_server (10.200.0.2) reachable: 0% loss, low RTT.\n  - load_balancer (10.200.0.7) reachable: 0% loss; RTT stable (host_1_1_1_1 shows some jitter, still low ms).\n  - web_server_0 (10.200.0.3) reachable: 0% loss; low RTT.\n  - dhcp_server (10.200.0.8) reachable: 0% loss; low ms (some jitter on one host).\n- Backend isolation (expected behavior validated):\n  - From hosts, 20.200.0.2 is unreachable with ICMP “Destination Net Unreachable” from the respective access gateway (10.x.1.1), confirming no route exposure to the private backend network.\n  - From the load balancer, backends 20.200.0.2/.3/.4 respond to ping with sub-ms RTTs.\n\nOSPF and routing\n- All tested routers show stable OSPF adjacencies in Full state:\n  - Core: router_core_1, router_core_2, router_core_3 adjacency matrices full with their peers.\n  - Distribution: router_dist_1_1 and router_dist_2_1 have Full neighbors to the core.\n  - Server-access: server_access_router has Full neighbor to core_3.\n- Route tables consistent:\n  - router_dist_1_1 learns 10.200.0.0/24 via core; local user VLAN 10.1.1.0/24 connected; other access networks and transit subnets present with appropriate metrics.\n  - server_access_router has 10.200.0.0/24 connected and learns all user subnets via core. No route to 20.200.0.0/24 is present (correct, maintains backend isolation).\n- No signs of flapping, incomplete neighbors, or missing LSAs observed.\n\nName resolution and service listeners\n- On hosts, getent resolves:\n  - web99.local -> 10.200.0.7 (load balancer)\n  - web0.local -> 10.200.0.3 (web_server_0)\n- Netstat:\n  - load_balancer: nginx listening on 0.0.0.0:80.\n  - web_server_0..3: Apache listening on 0.0.0.0:80.\n- Nginx configuration on load_balancer:\n  - upstream web99 uses three backends: 20.200.0.2:80, 20.200.0.3:80, 20.200.0.4:80.\n  - LB has eth1 20.200.0.1/24 connected to backends, and eth0 10.200.0.7/24 for client-facing access. Default route via 10.200.0.1 is present, as expected.\n\nHTTP behavior\n- web99.local (through load balancer) from both test hosts:\n  - HTTP/1.1 200 OK; total time typically ~1.0–1.1 s; TTFB ~0.20–0.30 s; stable across tests.\n- web0.local (direct to web_server_0) from both test hosts:\n  - Total times ~2.0–2.4 s; TTFB significantly higher ~1.2–1.6 s.\n- LB serves a large page (Content-Length ~262 KB) with good responsiveness; backend distribution appears functional (and backends are reachable from LB).\n\nPolicy validation: backend isolation\n- From hosts, backend subnet 20.200.0.0/24 is not reachable (no route), matching design constraint that backends are not directly accessible to users.\n- From LB, backends are reachable and respond promptly (sub-ms ping), confirming the LB-to-backend path is healthy.\n\nDetected anomalies\n\n- No critical reachability or routing anomalies found. OSPF is stable; all service subnets reachable where expected; DNS resolution correct; HTTP OK via LB and to web0.local.\n\nMinor performance observation\n- web_server_0 (web0.local) exhibits higher TTFB (~1.3–1.6 s) and longer total times (~2.0–2.4 s) than traffic through the load balancer.\n  - Localization: This is specific to web_server_0 application responses. Network path shows low latency and no packet loss; other HTTP paths (via LB) have significantly lower TTFB.\n  - Likely root cause domain: application/server-side performance on web_server_0, not a network routing or transport issue.\n\nConclusions\n- Network health: Good. OSPF adjacencies are Full and stable, routing tables are correct, and required services are reachable.\n- Backend access control: Correct; 20.200.0.0/24 is isolated from hosts and only accessible from the load balancer.\n- DNS and HTTP service delivery: Functional; load balancer returns 200 OK with stable performance.\n- Observed anomaly: Elevated TTFB on web0.local, localized to the web_server_0 host/service. No network device fault implicated.", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 15991, "output_tokens": 5338, "total_tokens": 21329, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 14976}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 3904}}}
